# Chapter 13 — Slat

SLAT is Motoi Scheme's homoiconic serialization format. Same reader
as your source code. Two file framings — `.slat` for hand-authored
documents, `.slatl` for line-delimited streams. Twenty-two primitives.
Canonical byte form for signing.

This chapter is the language-level summary. The full story is in the
**Book of SLAT** — sixteen chapters and ten appendices dedicated to
the format.

## The six API surfaces

```
slat-loads text        → one value        (single-form)
slat-load stream       → iterator          (line-delimited)
slat-load-doc stream   → one value        (whole-document)
slat-dumps value       → canonical string
slat-dump iter stream  → line-delimited writer
slat-dump-doc v stream → whole-document writer
```

Six functions. Learn them once; they're the same in every binding.

## Dumps

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(slat-dumps '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\" :by 'sakura))
</pre>

Produces canonical form: keys sorted, no comments, one space between
tokens.

## Loads

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(slat-loads \"(event :by 'sakura :kind \\\"card.opened\\\" :ts 1)\")
</pre>

Returns a slat-record.

## Round-trip

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(equal?
  '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\")
  (slat-loads (slat-dumps '(event :ts 1 :kind \"card.opened\"))))
</pre>

`#t`. The property CI enforces. Every value round-trips.

## The two framings

- `.slat` — whole-document. Zero or one top-level record. Newlines
  permitted inside records. Hand-authorable.
- `.slatl` — line-delimited. One record per line. Streamable,
  tail-able, grep-able.

Same grammar. The extension is the framing choice.

## Canonicalization

Same value → same bytes. Every writer. Every binding. Eleven rules,
enforced by the canonical writer. See Book of SLAT Chapter 8 and
Appendix D for the rules.

## Content addressing and signing

Canonical bytes hash to a stable content ID (sha256). CIDs sign with
ed25519. Chapter 9 and 10 of the Book of SLAT walk the full pipeline.

## Auto-assembly

The reader recognizes fifteen registered types (see Book of SLAT
Chapter 5) and rehydrates them to native objects. Unknown types come
back as generic records; they still round-trip. Consumers register
new types with `(define-slat-type …)`.

> **Sakura says**
>
> *SLAT is what I write to disk when I want a shape that both my
> JavaScript reader and my Python reader agree on to the byte. It is
> also what I read on the wire, and what my own source code looks
> like. One shape, all the way down.*

